occurrences.line_text: At last as chaunst them by a forest side
At last his mightie ghost gan deepe to grone,
That at the last she gan to breath out liuing aire.
Hard helpe at need. So deare thee babe I bought,
Him so I sought, and so at last I found
Whom thus at gaze, the Palmer gan to bord
And kindling fire at her faire burning eye,
At last when fayling breath began to faint,
Till that at last they to a Castle came,
Him at the threshold met, and well did enterprize.
Who all this while were at their wanton rest,
Where he abode, themselues at discord fell,
And at his first arriuall, them began
That at the last suppressing fury mad,
For both did at their second sister grutch,
Did see and grieue at his bold fashion;
At last when lust of meat and drinke was ceast,
At last when they had markt the chaunged skyes,
And ayme at him, fell flat to ground for feare,
Streight at his foot in base humilitee,
To serue at court in view of vaunting eye;
Till that at length with Archimage they meet:
The man was much abashed at his boast;
At which bold word that boaster gan to quake,
At his commaund, and reared him vp light
At last they heard a horne, that shrilled cleare
Kindled aboue at th'heauenly makers light,
And at her backe a bow and quiuer gay,
When she at last him spying thus bespake;
In mind to marke the beast. At which sad stowre,
Seeing at last her selfe from daunger rid,
Abroad in armes, at home in studious kind
And grieued at her flight; yet durst he not
Perdie (said Trompart) let her passe at will,
Then at the aymed marke, which he had eide:
But as a blindfold Bull at randon fares,
Who him gainstriuing, nought at all preuaild:
And furious fits at earst quite weren quaild:
Being at last recured, he gan inquire,
At last such grace I found, and meanes I wrought,
He promised to bring me at that howre,
When I at her my murdrous blade did bend,
Sore chauffed at my stay in such a cace,
For Guyons lookes, but scornefull eyglaunce at him shot.
Abandon this forestalled place at erst,
Or bide the chaunce at thine owne ieoperdie.
The knight at his great boldnesse wondered,
With his bright blade did smite at him so fell,
And shund the marke, at which it should be ment,
At him so fiercely, that the vpper marge
Exceeding wroth was Guyon at that blow,
Till at the last all breathlesse, wearie, faint
At last he was compeld to cry perforse,
The knight was greatly moued at his plaint,
For to dilate at large, but vrged sore
To laugh at shaking of the leaues light,
Faire Sir (quoth she) be not displeasd at all;
Ne wind and weather at his pleasure call:
And therewithall he fiercely at him flew,
And at their feet her selfe most humbly feld,
Yet at her speach their rages gan relent,
For much he wondred at that vncouth sight;
The varlet at his plaint was grieu'd so sore,
What hellish furie hath at earst thee hent?
At last he came vnto a gloomy glade,
And though him selfe were at the sight dismayd,
What art thou man, (if man at all thou art)
At thy commaund lo all these mountaines bee;
That money can thy wantes at will supply?
At the well head the purest streames arise:
At length they came into a larger space,
At last him to a litle dore he brought,
To wonder at the sight: for till that day,
The warlike Elfe much wondred at this tree,
To which if he inclined had at all,
Which to that shadie delue him brought at last,
In senselesse dreame; which sight at first him sore aghast.
Were fixed at his backe, to cut his ayerie wayes.
For euill is at hand him to offend.
At last him turning to his charge behight,
At last he spide, where towards him did pace
And enuie base, to barke at sleeping fame:
Where at his feete, with sorrowfull demaine
Till that at last, when he aduantage spyde,
At proud Cymochles, whiles his shield was wyde,
Nought could he hurt, but still at ward did ly:
His robbed whelpes, and at the last them fond
But euer at Pyrrochles when he smit,
Long trembling still he stood: at last thus sayd;
With his owne sword he fierce at him did flye,
At last when as the Sarazin perceiu'd,
For losse of thousand liues, to dye at her desire.
Fiersly at first those knights they did assaile,
Hewing and slashing at their idle shades;
As when a swarme of Gnats at euentide
Early and late it rong, at euening and at prime.
Early and late it rong, at euening and at prime.
At th'upper end there sate, yclad in red
Some plaid with strawes, some idly sat at ease;
But at these straungers presence euery one did hush.
The Prince was inly moued at her speach,
That Guyon meruayld at her vncouth cace:
Faire Sir at that, which ye so much embrace?
And wondred at his endlesse exercise,
At bold Canutus; but of him was slaine anon.
At last ripe age bad him surrender late
Exceld at Athens all the learned preace,
Behold the boyling Bathes at Cairbadon,
Yet he at last contending to excell
Who him at first well vsed euery way;
At last resolu'd likewise to proue the rest,
And inly tremble at the memory
Whom he at sea found wandring from their wayes,
Ne had they footing found at last perdie,
Then they which sought at first their helping hand,
Of British bloud, all sitting at his bord;
Th'eternall markes of treason may at Stonheng vew.
So now entombed lyes at Stoneheng by the heath.
Or th'Authour selfe could not at least attend
At last quite rauisht with delight, to heare
Where them awaited ready at the ford
And therewith all attonce at him let fly
There follow'd fast at hand two wicked Hags,
With which at him a cruell shaft he sent:
Soone to him raught, and fierce at him did ride,
Vnto his Tygres taile, and shot at him apace.
At last breakes forth with furious vnrest,
Threw at his foe, who was right well aware
And strooke at him so sternely, that he made
But freshly as at first, prepard himselfe to fight.
Ne what to say, ne what to doe at all;
At need, till now, he lightly threw away,
Stoupes at a flying heron with proud disdaine,
Doth rore at them in vaine, and with great terror raue.
At last them driuen hath to this despairefull drift.
At last farre off they many Islands spy,
Scoffing at him, that did her iustly wite,
Scarse had he said, when hard at hand they spy
At last they in an Island did espy
And for your ruine at the last awayt.
Till that at last the weather gan to cleare,
Much wondred Guyon at the faire aspect
Art, and that Art at nature did repine;
Gazing a while at his vnwonted guise;
In which they creeping did at last display
Which now awaking, fierce at them gan fly,
At last as through an open plaine they yode,
At length they came into a forrest wyde,
At sight whereof the people stand aghast:
At last as nigh out of the wood she came,
Like dastard Curres, that hauing at a bay
Still did she roue at her with crafty glaunce
Of her false eyes, that at her hart did ayme,
Which spent in vaine, at last she told her briefe,
But inly sigh'd. At last the royall Mayd
Wherewith enrag'd she fiercely at them flew,
At last the passion past she thus him answered.
At tilt or tourney, or like warlike game,
And yield the pray of loue to lothsome death at last.
But he it knew at home before he hard
Yet wist her life at last must lincke in that same knot.
Did smyle full smoothly at her weetlesse wofull stound.
Yet wist, she was not well at ease perdy,
As it an Earth-quake were; at last she thus bespake.
So that at last a little creeping sleepe
At last she her auisd, that he, which made
He nought was moued at their entrance bold:
At her smooth speeches, weeting inly well,
Yet is no Fary borne, ne sib at all
But at the last to th'importunity
Where at Cadwallin wroth, shall forth issew,
And sighing sore, at length him thus bespake;
Nor vengeaunce huge relent it selfe at last?
At last the fury past, to former hew
At last the Nourse in her foolhardy wit
At last their wayes so fell, that they mote part
Till that to the sea-coast at length she her addrest.
At length allay, and stint thy stormy strife,
At last blow vp some gentle gale of ease,
The world in darkenesse dwels, till that at last
A mightie man at armes, and mickle fame
Great Neptune stood amazed at their sight,
And eke himselfe mournd at their mournfull plight,
Stood gaping at their gate, and wondred them to see.
To the long raynes, at her commaundement:
And that they might him handle more at will,
He loued, and at last her wombe did fill
Her teme at her commaundement quiet stands,
At last they came vnto a double way,
At last of her farre off he gained vew:
But to and fro at disauenture strayd;
It lets not scarse this Prince to breath at all,
To finde some issue thence, till that at last
But he sets nought at all by Florimell:
At least eternall meede shall you abide.
And out of sight escaped at the least;
With that at him a quiu'ring dart he threw,
Him kept from landing at his wished will;
At last through wrath and vengeaunce making way,
And droue at him with all his might and maine
And therewith shot an arrow at the lad;
And strooke at him with force so violent,
And groning inly deepe, at last his eyes,
And where their Lady was, arriued at the last.
Ah God, what other could he do at least,
Till that through weaknesse he was forst at last,
At last she her bethought, that she had not
At last they both agreed, her seeming grieued
As it at first created was of yore.
Her hart was pierst with pittie at the sight,
Continuall, both meeting at one time:
His force, at last perforce a downe did ly,
So long she trauelled, till at length she came
And came at last in weary wretched plight
At last turning her feare to foolish wrath,
In mischiefe, was much moued at so pitteous sight.
She was astonisht at her heauenly hew,
He comming home at vndertime, there found
Softly at last he gan his mother aske,
So both at her, and each at other wondered.
So both at her, and each at other wondered.
Ne once to stay to rest, or breath at large,
At that same last extremitie full sore,
So safetie found at sea, which she found not at land.
So safetie found at sea, which she found not at land.
But greedily long gaping at the sight,
At last in vaine was forst to turne his flight,
That at the last his fiercenesse gan abate,
He left his captiue Beast at liberty,
And at her ran: she hauing him descryde,
But still when him at hand she did espy,
At length he spide, whereas that wofull Squire,
For at that berth another Babe she bore,
Me seely wretch she so at vauntage caught,
To wander through the world abroad at will,
And at the twelue monethes end should bring their names
Ah gentle Squire (quoth he) tell at one word,
But was as farre at last, as when I first begon.
At those proud words that other knight begonne
The land for sea, at randon there to raunge:
At last when droncke with drowsinesse, he woke,
To fetch from sea, that ye at land lost late;
That went at will, withouten carde or sayle,
Ne to recomfort her at all preuayld;
And neuer suffred her to be at rest:
Which speaking token sheweth at the least
Yet has full large to liue, and spend at libertie.
That this faire many were compeld at last,
Had them surprised. At last auizing right,
But most they meruail[e]d at her cheualree,
And company at meat, to do them more delight.
And sent close messages of loue to her at will.
He rou'd at her, and told his secret care:
She sent at him one firie dart, whose hed
Ne paine at all; for he so oft had tryde
She was empassiond at that piteous act,
Then sighing soft awhile, at last she thus:
That floures so fresh at morne, and fades at euening late?
That floures so fresh at morne, and fades at euening late?
At last in Latium he did arriue,
So huge a scope at first him seemed best,
At last by fatall course they driuen were
In speaking, many false belgardes at her let fly.
Thou seest all, yet none at all sees thee;
At hand with humble pride, and pleasing guile,
Did clap her hands, and ioyed at that dolefull sight.
Laught at his foolish labour spent in waste;
At last when sorrow he saw booted nought,
At last resoluing, like a pilgrim pore,
And euer his faint hart much earned at the sight.
The Boaster at him sternely bent his browe,
The wretched man at his imperious speach,
Of whom a knight, no knight at all perdee,
At last he thus; Thou clod of vilest clay,
The gentle Lady, loose at randon left,
At wilde aduenture, like a forlorne weft,
At night, when all they went to sleepe, he vewd,
At last with irkesome trouble she abrayd;
But she it all refused at one word,
That he thereby receiu'd no hurt at all,
That at the last he found a caue with entrance small.
That she at last came to a fountaine sheare,
At last forth breaking into bitter plaintes
At least it faire endeuour will apply.
Thus she at length perswaded him to rise,
Nor ward to wait at morne and euening late,
How towards her he rusht, and smiled at his pryde.
And at the vpper end of that faire rowme,
With which he shot at randon, when him list,
At last she spyde at that roomes vpper end,
At last she spyde at that roomes vpper end,
And merueild at his strange intendiment;
That at his backe a brode Capuccio had,
At that wide orifice her trembling hart
At last that mightie chaine, which round about
And gaue her leaue at pleasure forth to passe.
Where let them wend at will, whilest here I doe respire.
At last she came vnto the place, where late
At this same furrowes end, till a new day:
Now cease your worke, and at your pleasure play:
To such therefore I do not sing at all,
Lo thus they rode, till at the last they spide
As plaine as at the first, when they were fresh and greene.
Now growen great, at first of little seedes,
For she at first was borne of hellish brood,
So much they did, that at the last they brake
Both foolish knights, I can but laugh at both,
I saw him haue your Amoret at will,
And thrise he drew it backe: so did at last forbeare.
And Paridell her scornd, and set at nought,
And inly grudge at him, that he had sped so well.
And deadly points at eithers breast to bend,
As when two warlike Brigandines at sea,
Do greatly stand amaz'd at such vnwonted wonder.
At length they both vpstarted in amaze;
Who lookt a little vp at that his speech,
That they at last their wrothfull hands let fall,
Who as they now approched nigh at hand,
Borne at one burden in one happie morne;
These three so noble babes to bring forth at one clap.
And when at last she had beheld her fill,
And chaung'd at pleasure for those impes of thine.
That euery houre they knocke at deathes gate?
And at th'one side sixe iudges were dispos'd,
At puffe of euery storme doth stagger here and theare.
Againe he droue at him with double might,
And with such furie backe at him it heft,
And heau'd his murdrous axe at him with mighty sway.
For seeing it at hand, he swaru'd asyde,
Strikes at an Heron with all his bodies sway,
He can let driue at him with all his power,
With heapes of strokes, which he at him let flie,
Sir Triamond at last full faint and feeble stood.
And at that instant reaching forth his sweard
So both at once fell dead vpon the field,
They weened sure the warre was at an end,
At last arriuing by the listes side,
To let them passe at will, for dread of shame.
At which they all gan laugh full merrily:
At which his vaine excuse they all gan smile,
Till that at length vpon th'appointed day,
With that, at him his beam-like speare he aimed,
A mightie speare eftsoones at him he bent;
It chaunst Sir Satyrane his steed at last,
All which at once huge strokes on him did pound,
With that he driues at them with dreadfull might,
There might ye see loose steeds at randon ronne,
He at his first incomming, charg'd his spere
At him, that first appeared in his sight:
Him at the first encounter downe he smote,
He at his entrance charg'd his powrefull speare
At Artegall, in middest of his pryde,
And ran at him with all his might and maine;
His speare he feutred, and at him it bore;
Full many others at him likewise ran:
At last the most redoubted Britonesse,
That all men wondred at the vncouth sight,
Till that at last the gentle Amoret
Yet at her choice they all did greatly muse.
And at them both Sir Paridell did loure.
At last to Braggadochio selfe alone
And hauing long beheld, at last enquired
About the house, at sent of stranger guest:
That at the last his wearie sprite opprest
The things that day most minds, at night doe most appeare.
And voide his course: at which so suddain case
And therewithall at him right furiously she strooke.
At length when as he saw her hastie heat
And lashing dreadfully at euery part,
At last his lucklesse hand he heau'd on hie,
And therewith stroke at her so hideouslie,
At last fell humbly downe vpon his knee,
She arm'd her tongue, and thought at him to scold;
That at the length vnto a bay he brought her,
At last through many vowes which forth he pour'd,
At last when all her speeches she had spent,
That at the last he did himselfe attaine,
With dreadfull strokes let driue at him so sore,
Who all to her at large, as hapned, did relate.
Right sore agrieued at her sharpe reproofe,
Her mortall arrowes she at him did threat,
At last when long he follow'd had in vaine,
That out of all mens knowledge he was worne at last.
Yet he him knew not, ne auiz'd at all,
At which his vncouth guise and vsage quaint
That at the last of all his woe and wrong

Till that at length into that forrest wide,
He her beholding, at her feet downe fell,
But wondred much at his so selcouth case,
But most was moued at the piteous vew

And rayle at them with grudgefull discontent,
Whose noble kind at first was sure of heauenly seed.
At last when they were passed out of sight,
The stone, which passed straunger at him threw;
At length they spide, where towards them with speed
He all the way did rage at that same Squire,
With dreadfull weapon aymed at his head;
And therewith smote at him with all his might.
He smote at him with all his might and maine,
Then gan the Prince at leasure to inquire
And for his loue him promist libertie at last.
And at his will may whom he list restore,
Yet ouerrul'd at last, he did to me agree.
The Dwarfe cald at the doore of Amyas,
Thenceforth I found more fauour at her hand,
And graunt more scope to me to walke at large.
Thus as they talked, loe where nigh at hand
Thus gazing long, at them much wondred he,
But cause of feare sure had she none at all
At length they came, whereas a troupe of Knights
So eke lou'd Blandamour, but yet at pleasure
And wondred at their impacable stoure,
So dreadfull strokes each did at other driue,
Who wondring much at that so sodaine fit,
At Scudamour, both his professed fone.

At whose request he gan him selfe aduise
And told at large how that same errant Knight,

Since of my loue at length I rest assured,
Ran fierce at me, that fire glaunst from his horses hoofe.
Till at the last I spide within the same,
For oftentimes faint hearts at first espiall
And gnasht his yron tuskes at that displeasing sight.
So all the world by thee at first was made,
O graunt that of my loue at last I may not misse.
I spyde, where at the Idoles feet apart
Ne rov'd at randon after gazers guyse,
At sight thereof she was with terror queld,
To laugh at me, and fauour my pretence,
Her constant mind could moue at all he saw,
At last to Tryphon she for helpe did hie,
Till now at last relenting, she to him was wed.
Stood still by him astonisht at his lore,
No not the stately Seuerne grudg'd at all,
All which long sundred, doe at last accord
So flowing all from one, all one at last become.
Were present at this great solemnity:
The manner of the Gods when they at banquet bee.
Ye Gods of seas, if any Gods at all
He where he list goes loose, and laughes at me.
At last when as no meanes he could inuent,
And chyde at him, that made her misbelieue:
It's now at earst become a stonie one;
And men themselues, the which at first were framed
So now all range, and doe at randon roue
Till they arriue at their last ruinous decay.
Much was he moued at that ruefull sight;
And at one stroke cropt off her head with scorne,
Whom at the first he ghessed by his looke,
And streight at him with all his force did go.
And sternly gan repine at his beheast;
It will be at the Castle of the strond;
Then doth he take the spoile of them at will,
They each at other tyrannously flew;
So Artegall at length him forst forsake
And then no ods at all in him he fownd:
And with his iron flale at it let flie,
That at the length he has yrent the dore,
At length found out, whereas she hidden lay

Till that at length nigh to the sea they drew;
For at the first they all created were
Doe eate the earth, it is no more at all:
And rudely stroke at him on euery side:
But when at them he with his flaile gan lay,
Flowne at a flush of Ducks, foreby the brooke,
The sunne at length his ioyous face doth cleare:
Some blisfull houres at last must needes appeare;
But at the last the trompets did proclame
That all men stood amaz'd, & at his might did wonder.
He much was mou'd at so vnworthie shame,
Is not (I wager) Florimell at all;
That all men wonder at her colours pride;
At the remembrance of their knauerie.
Ladies can laugh at Ladies, Knights at Knights,

As thing at randon left, to whom he list.
Reioyced at his miserable case,
But when she saw at last, that he ne would
From deathes dore, at which he lately lay,
And at the Porter, skorning them so few,
Like a fell Lionesse at him she flew,
Her proud foote setting, at his head did leuell,
Weening at once her wrath on him to wreake,
With dreadfull force he flies at her byliue,
She at the first encounter on him ran
Weening at last to win aduantage new;
For with his trenchant blade at the next blow
With her sharpe Cemitare at him she flew,
With indignation, at her vaunting vaine,
And at her strooke with puissance fearefull fell;
Thinking at once both head and helmet to haue raced.
